text: Going to spoil this disappointing film by telling you a few of the bad scenes to look out for: 1) Hank McCoy (Beast) going out of character by teaming up with Erik (Magneto) to kill Jean Grey. 2) Erik (Magneto) going out of character by telling Jean Grey to get out of his community after realizing she was wanted by the human authorities. 3) The US government's relationship with the X-Men swings wildly to the point of near-amusement. After Jean Grey went out of control in public, the President suddenly cuts off the direct phone line earlier established between him and Professor Xavier. 4) The villain Vuk's appearances are just about as mesmerizing as that of Justice League's Steppenwolf and Thor: The Dark World's Malekith.

text: First of all, I’m pretty much aware that there are lots of bad reviews out there. I’m sure that you’ve seen them as well. The thing is, “X-Men: Dark Phoenix” is not as bad as what critics are saying. In my opinion, this film is better than “X-Men: Apocalypse” and the previous Phoenix Saga adaptation, “X-Men: The Last Stand”.  ”X-Men: Dark Phoenix” clearly shows that Sophie Turner is strong enough to carry this film, she’s amazing. Even though the script for the film is a bit generic, not to mention that there are some cringeworthy ones. The first and the second act of the film are a bit slow, however, things are getting 180° different in the third act. By different, I mean in a good way. The entire soundtrack of the film is excellent, as the entire score is composed by Hans Zimmer.  From the recurring cast, James McAvoy’s Professor X and Michael Fassbender’s Magneto got their awesome chemistry as usual. Jennifer Lawrence and Nicholas Hoult are also amazing. I can finally feel the chemistry of Tye Sheridan’s Scott with Sophie Turner’s Jean. It’s also nice knowing that Kodi Smit-McPhee’s Nightcrawler and Alexandra Shipp’s Storm finally deserve more spotlight. The newcomer Jessica Chastain, she’s good but her villain role is weak, and I’m not talking about her powers. It’s just I can’t feel her role as a villain. Here’s an advice, keep your eyes sharp to see some cameos of X-Men’s familiar mutants from the comics.  In the end, despite what the critics are saying, “X-Men: Dark Phoenix” is still quite enjoyable and entertaining. A decent way to end FOX’s X-Men franchise, kinda.  7/10  If you’re wondering for a credit scene, the answer is no, there are no mid or post credit scene for this film.  #XMen #DarkPhoenix

text: Before I comment, I want to let anyone know reading this I don't know a lot about Jean's character from the comics, so this movie will be the second way for me to witness what her powers can do (Whether good or bad, I have seen The Last Stand).  But from what I've seen in the trailer, there are a lot of similarities to what I feel with my depression. I push people away, and end up hurting them because I don't feel like I deserve their help, OR I don't want their help because I want to believe I can deal with it on my own and not drag people along with my problems. I'm sure this wasn't intentional, but seeing these parallels gets me more interested in seeing how this version of the X-Men is going to be sent off.

text: Looks like the director of this movie has never read the comic or at least watched the tv version of The Dark Phoenix Saga.  Jean Grey as The Dark Phoenix is confident, narcissistic and cruel most of the time... Phoenix has unlimited power, she is omnipotent. Phoenix even eats entire stars... all I can see in the trailer is a weak weak weak version of Phoenix, a melodramatic Jean Grey dealing with internal problems most of the time and seems like the entire movie will be like that.  There is always a fire effect surrounding Jean Grey in the Phoenix Saga... that detail is very important to show the Phoenix power... even Captain Marvel looks more Phoenix with those effects. Now we'll have to wait like 10 more years to see if some director creates a better Phoenix-Jean Grey...

text: Ever since Chris Claremont stared writing for Marvel and created the Phoenix Saga, DC, other companies, and Hollywood as decades past saw its success and did it with their characters and a trend started. Our changing times with war other bad stuff made this trend even more popular.  So now superheroes are not superheroes any more.  They are now only angst filled emo kids who cry all the time and  kill people.  That's all they do.  They are now merely vessels for catharthsis for the fans may have a terrible home life or are bullied at school, which is no fault of their own.  I used to be bullied too. You used to come to see these movies to escape for two hours from all the crap that life throws at you. Now that crap gets thrown back in your face.

text: Here's what I expect the film to deliver: 1. Tell the story of the phoenix in a reasonable fashion, about how it started out, and how it developed inside of Jean, along with what Professor X did and should've done instead. 2. Tell us what happens between "X-Men: Apocalypse" and "Logan". We all saw the last of the X-Men at the end of "Days of Future Past", and then the last of leftover X-Men in "Deadpool 2", but no proper explanation for the absence of most of the important characters, or a proper send-off. 3. Execute a perfect ending to this whole X-Men universe by finishing leftover character arcs and making sure everyone finds a suitable ending. 4. Fill up the void about some important characters that could've been otherwise depicted better but weren't, like Victor Creed, Sunspot, Bishop, maybe make a reference to the Fantastic Four existing in their universe now that it's all about to end anyway. That last bit would blow my mind.

author: Dan C

text: I am a huge Fox X-Men film fan, but I always felt like the narrative concluded with Logan. I was hoping I was wrong since this film fits in before Logan, but because of Days of Future Past, we know that the only characters at risk are Magneto, Mystique, Nightcrawler, and Quicksilver, the rest, including Jean, will be fine in the end. I was not a huge fan of Sophie Turner being cast as Jean since she felt mean and cold in the last film and this continues to prove I was right about her lack of on screen warmth to care enough for the character. I always felt that Jennifer Lawrence and Sophie Turner were two of the weakest links in this series, and yet they focus so strongly on them, which is a mistake. The focus should be on Cyclops and Jean completely for this film. That is where X3 went wrong (of many places) and that's where this is going wrong. But it's the end of the Fox X-Men films so it's not a big deal that this trailer doesn't look too promising to be a great conclusion. I can rest easy knowing it just fits in between Apocalypse and the end of Days of Future Past and Logan. So for me it's more filler. Seeing Hugh Jackman show up (which will never happen) again would probably be a very pleasant surprise in this....but ain't gonna happen, I know. It's really a film series focused on his character.

text: It’s amazing how Fox doesn’t understand The X-Men. It’s the second Dark Phoenix movie and they are still unable to make anything good. Why we still have Hunger Games girl in it? Will Magneto kills millions again and be forgiven as usual? Fox, do you want to make a good X-Men movie? Then forget about Mystique, mutant prejudice and Magneto/Xavier romance. You’ve drained too much out of it already. X-Men is much more than that. Just keep to Claremont/Cockrum/Byrne/Smith era. Don’t go beyond it. Make a first movie that looks like the first Avengers, but with smaller scope (no pointless destruction of entire cities), then a second movie like Guardians of the Galaxy, and the third movie can be whatever you want, if you’ve done the first two right. And do NOT make “Wolverine and those X-guys” again. It’s supposed to be an ensemble, not a vehicle for a single actor.

text: I'm gonna miss this franchise and Fox as a whole. Some of my favorite movies were done by this studio and seeing it disappear and almost all of it's licenses go to Disney is heartwrenching.   I don't hate everything Disney does but the tone is almost always the same and you don't get certain films from them because they're too adult. They take little to no risks and everything feels repetitive and formulaic. Gotta hand it to them tho, the audience loves the formula so much that almost everything they make being good or terrible is going to make money.  Still, I feel that 10 years from now we will look back and think "this factory made movies that we have now have lost so much heart and creativity that I wish the buyout never happened"

text: Wow, that was really cool! This looks really good and it feels like a movie intended as the last chapter or a wrap-up of the franchise. It also feels like the characters have truly aged between movies. Xavier just sounds and seems older,  like he's slowly morphing into Patrick Stewart and the makeup on Beast actually looks like Kelsey Grammer's makeup from the The Last Stand. text: I actually like that it resembles The Last Stand. I mean, I really like Last Stand to begin with, but the fact that certain visuals are similar to how they are in that movie, shows some real consistency. Like, history is repeating itself, or playing out the same way. It sort of shows the dangers of time travel, Wolverine went back in time to save the future, but in doing so, the timeline was affected severely, as in Phoenix being awakened much sooner due to what ever happened on that space mission. But even so, events are playing out similar, recognize the street from the beginning of the trailer, how about the shot of Scott confronting a full on Dark Phoenix Jean, calling her name, where have we seen something like that before. None of this I see as negative, it's interesting to see and might actually help the credibility of Last Stand, seeing and alternate version of that movies events.
